label:
# Study for Marine Protected Area managers: # What does your workforce include?

Thanks for participating in this voluntary study— your input is valuable. Please consider the information in this about document and ask any questions you may have before deciding if you will participate. You can also watch a short video about why this project matters here.

As the world moves toward protecting 30% of the ocean by 2030, the Marine Conservation Institute (MPAtlas), eOceans, the Leibniz-IZW, the IUCN World Commission on Protected Areas, Re:wild, and Blue Nature Alliance have partnered to understand the MPA workforce — this includes staff, employees, and others who have a formal role actively contributing to achieving the goals of a specific MPA.

This study aims to create a clear picture of the workforce behind current MPAs and give us an idea of what may be needed as the number of MPAs grows.

### Here's how it works:
  • Part A: 2 questions: Let's identify your MPA.
  • Part B: 4 questions: Tell us about this MPA.
  • Part C: 4 questions: Tell us about you.
  • Part D: 2 (optional) questions: Tell us more?

️🎬 Before you jump in, don't hesitate to watch a walkthrough of the survey here.

💡 Click here to learn about Data Access, Risks, Support, Funders, and more.

🪼 Thank you!
Your input is invaluable to this study and will provide crucial insights for others working on MPAs like you.
Together, we’re strengthening the global MPA network.

Sincerely,
Dr. Christine Ward-Paige, eOceans
Beth Pike, Marine Conservation Institute
Dr. Alexandre Courtiol, Leibniz-IZW

label:
## 1: Who works on this specific MPA? ### Including yourself, how many formal staff work on this MPA, and in what roles?

🦀 Report as full-time equivalents (enter values smaller than 1 for less than full time).
🪼 If staff split their time between roles, please divide them across categories if you can OR choose the one that is most appropriate.

💡 Examples:

  • 1.00 = full-time, working all year
  • 0.50 = part-time
  • 0.25 = seasonal
  • 0.10 = occasional
Click here to see more detailed examples. When filling out more complex workforce numbers, you can estimate how much time each person spends on this specific MPA by using decimals to reflect partial time.
Here are three quick examples:

  1. 🐙 Split between roles:
    If someone divides their time equally between being a ranger and doing admin/support work, count 0.5 for this person in each of the two appropriate categories.
  2. 🪼 Split between the MPA and other projects:
    If someone works 50% on this MPA and 50% on other sites or programs (e.g. fisheries or another MPA), count only a total of 0.5 for this person across the appropriate categories.
  3. 🦈 Count seasonal and occasional workers:
    If someone only works on this MPA for 5 weeks per year, count a total of 0.1 for this person across the appropriate categories.
